            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the Altman Z-Score?</h2>
              <p>
                The Altman Z-Score is a credit-risk model developed by Edward
                Altman to estimate the probability that a company will enter
                financial distress or bankruptcy within the next 1–2 years. It
                combines five accounting ratios into a single score, then
                compares that score to empirically derived “distress”, “grey”,
                and “safe” zones.
              </p>
              <p>
                Analysts, lenders, and investors use the Z-Score as a quick
                screening tool alongside other metrics such as leverage,
                interest coverage, and cash flow.
              </p>

              <h2>Altman Z-Score formulas</h2>

              <h3>1. Original Z-Score (public manufacturing firms)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Model:</strong> Publicly traded manufacturing
                  companies
                </p>
                <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
                <p>\( Z = 1.2X_1 + 1.4X_2 + 3.3X_3 + 0.6X_4 + 1.0X_5 \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \(X_1 = \dfrac{\text{Working Capital}}{\text{Total
                    Assets}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(X_2 = \dfrac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Total
                    Assets}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(X_3 = \dfrac{\text{EBIT}}{\text{Total Assets}}\)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(X_4 = \dfrac{\text{Market Value of Equity}}{\text{Total
                    Liabilities}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(X_5 = \dfrac{\text{Sales}}{\text{Total Assets}}\)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Z’-Score (private manufacturing firms)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Model:</strong> Privately held manufacturing companies
                </p>
                <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( Z' = 0.717X_1 + 0.847X_2 + 3.107X_3 + 0.420X_4 + 0.998X_5
                  \)
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \(X_1 = \dfrac{\text{Working Capital}}{\text{Total
                    Assets}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(X_2 = \dfrac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Total
                    Assets}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(X_3 = \dfrac{\text{EBIT}}{\text{Total Assets}}\)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(X_4 = \dfrac{\text{Book Value of Equity}}{\text{Total
                    Liabilities}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(X_5 = \dfrac{\text{Sales}}{\text{Total Assets}}\)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Z’’-Score (non-manufacturing & emerging markets)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Model:</strong> Non-manufacturing firms and emerging
                  markets
                </p>
                <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
                <p>\( Z'' = 6.56X_1 + 3.26X_2 + 6.72X_3 + 1.05X_4 \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \(X_1 = \dfrac{\text{Working Capital}}{\text{Total
                    Assets}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(X_2 = \dfrac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Total
                    Assets}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(X_3 = \dfrac{\text{EBIT}}{\text{Total Assets}}\)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(X_4 = \dfrac{\text{Book Value of Equity}}{\text{Total
                    Liabilities}}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>Sales/Assets term is omitted in this variant.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h2>How to interpret the Altman Z-Score</h2>
              <p>
                The cut-offs differ slightly by model. Commonly used thresholds
                are:
              </p>

              <h3>Original Z-Score (public manufacturing)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Z &lt; 1.81</strong> – Distress zone (high bankruptcy
                  risk)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>1.81 ≤ Z ≤ 2.99</strong> – Grey zone (indeterminate)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Z &gt; 2.99</strong> – Safe zone (low bankruptcy risk)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Z’-Score (private manufacturing)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Z’ &lt; 1.23</strong> – Distress zone</li>
                <li><strong>1.23 ≤ Z’ ≤ 2.90</strong> – Grey zone</li>
                <li><strong>Z’ &gt; 2.90</strong> – Safe zone</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Z’’-Score (non-manufacturing / emerging markets)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Z’’ &lt; 1.10</strong> – Distress zone</li>
                <li><strong>1.10 ≤ Z’’ ≤ 2.60</strong> – Grey zone</li>
                <li><strong>Z’’ &gt; 2.60</strong> – Safe zone</li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                These thresholds are based on Altman’s empirical research and
                may be adjusted by practitioners for specific industries,
                regions, or time periods.
              </p>

              <h2>Step-by-step example</h2>
              <p>Suppose a public manufacturing firm reports (in USD):</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Working Capital = 250,000</li>
                <li>Total Assets = 1,000,000</li>
                <li>Retained Earnings = 150,000</li>
                <li>EBIT = 120,000</li>
                <li>Market Value of Equity = 500,000</li>
                <li>Total Liabilities = 600,000</li>
                <li>Sales = 900,000</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Compute the ratios:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>\(X_1 = 250{,}000 / 1{,}000{,}000 = 0.25\)</li>
                <li>\(X_2 = 150{,}000 / 1{,}000{,}000 = 0.15\)</li>
                <li>\(X_3 = 120{,}000 / 1{,}000{,}000 = 0.12\)</li>
                <li>\(X_4 = 500{,}000 / 600{,}000 \approx 0.83\)</li>
                <li>\(X_5 = 900{,}000 / 1{,}000{,}000 = 0.90\)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Plug into the original Z-Score formula:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( Z = 1.2(0.25) + 1.4(0.15) + 3.3(0.12) + 0.6(0.83) +
                  1.0(0.90) \)
                </p>
                <p>\( Z = 0.30 + 0.21 + 0.396 + 0.498 + 0.90 \approx 2.30 \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                A Z-Score of about 2.30 lies in the grey zone: not clearly
                distressed, but not comfortably safe either.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and best practices</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The model is
                  <strong>not suitable for banks or insurance companies</strong
                  >.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It relies on <strong>historical accounting data</strong>,
                  which may lag real-time conditions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It assumes
                  <strong>GAAP/IFRS-quality financial statements</strong>;
                  aggressive accounting can distort results.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use it as a <strong>screening tool</strong>, not a standalone
                  decision rule.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Combine with cash flow analysis, debt maturity profile,
                  covenants, and qualitative factors (management, industry
                  trends, etc.).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is a higher Altman Z-Score always better?</h3>
              <p>
                In general, yes: a higher Z-Score indicates lower estimated
                bankruptcy risk. However, extremely high scores may simply
                reflect low leverage or unusually high profitability and should
                be interpreted in context.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I recalculate the Z-Score?</h3>
              <p>
                Many analysts update the Z-Score each quarter when new financial
                statements are released, and more frequently during periods of
                stress or rapid change.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I compare Z-Scores across industries?</h3>
              <p>
                Comparisons are most meaningful within similar industries and
                regions. Capital intensity, margins, and leverage norms differ
                widely, so absolute thresholds may not translate perfectly
                across sectors.
              </p>
